<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-04-02T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-04-02T03:00:00-05:00" n="428" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d428">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4279: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-04-02T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">April 2,
                                        1922—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 6—1:25
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>127. The following is from Canton: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“April 1, 8 p.m. C. C. Wu informs me it was decided at Mukden,
                                    Sun to be President, Tsze [<hi rend="italic">Tuan?</hi>] Vice
                                    President with elimination of undesirable Anfu element,
                                    Government to be formed on federal lines, new Parliament to take
                                    the place of old Parliaments, Chang to support Sun with Liang as
                                    Premier. Hsu and Wu Pei-fu must accept or be eliminated.”
                                    (signed) Huston.<note n="24" xml:id="d428fn24">Jay Calvin
                                        Huston, vice consul at Canton.</note></p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>